filter() is an intermediate operation that selects elements from a stream based on a condition.

It accepts a Predicate<T> and returns a new stream containing only elements that satisfy the condition.

Method Signature
Stream<T> filter(Predicate<? super T> predicate)

Let's break it down:

Stream<T>

Return type.

👉 filter() returns a new Stream, not a List.

Predicate<? super T>

Parameter type.

👉 Predicate is a functional interface:

@FunctionalInterface
public interface Predicate<T> {
    boolean test(T t);
}

It takes one value and returns:

true → keep element
false → remove element
What Happens Internally

Given:

List<Integer> numbers =
        List.of(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);
numbers.stream()
       .filter(x -> x % 2 == 0)
       .forEach(System.out::println);

Java does roughly this:

for (Integer x : numbers) {
    if (x % 2 == 0) {
        System.out.println(x);
    }
}

Output:

2
4
filter() Is Lazy

This is very important.

Stream<String> stream =
        list.stream()
            .filter(s -> s.startsWith("A"));

At this point:

👉 Nothing happens yet.

The stream starts processing only when a terminal operation appears.

Example:

stream.forEach(System.out::println);

Now execution begins.

filter() Does Not Modify Data
List<String> fruits =
        List.of("Apple", "Banana", "Avocado");

fruits.stream()
      .filter(s -> s.startsWith("A"));

Original list:

[Apple, Banana, Avocado]

Still unchanged.

Chaining Multiple Filters
list.stream()
    .filter(s -> s.length() > 5)
    .filter(s -> s.startsWith("A"))
    .forEach(System.out::println);

Processing:

Apple     -> keep
Banana    -> remove
Avocado   -> keep

Output:

Avocado
Using Predicate Variables

Instead of:

.filter(x -> x > 10)

You can write:

Predicate<Integer> greaterThanTen =
        x -> x > 10;

numbers.stream()
       .filter(greaterThanTen)
       .forEach(System.out::println);
Combining Predicates
and()
Predicate<Integer> positive =
        x -> x > 0;

Predicate<Integer> even =
        x -> x % 2 == 0;

numbers.stream()
       .filter(positive.and(even))
       .forEach(System.out::println);
or()
.filter(positive.or(even))
negate()
.filter(even.negate())

👉 selects odd numbers

Return Type

Many beginners think:

List<String> result =
        list.stream()
            .filter(...)

❌ Compilation error

Because filter() returns:

Stream<String>

To get a List:

List<String> result =
        list.stream()
            .filter(...)
            .toList();
Complexity

For a stream with n elements:

.filter(...)

Time complexity:

O(n)

Because every element must be checked.

Common Interview Questions
Does filter() change the original collection?

❌ No

Is filter() terminal or intermediate?

✅ Intermediate

What does filter() return?

✅ Stream

Which functional interface does filter() use?

✅ Predicate

Summary
filter() selects elements based on a condition
accepts a Predicate
returns a new Stream
does not modify the original collection
is a lazy intermediate operation
complexity is O(n)
one of the most commonly used Stream methods
